[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1111},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F10\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F10\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F10\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F10\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1\u002F":1087,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fpython\u002F2021\u002F09\u002F10\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1\u002F":1096},"\u002Fpython\u002F20210910\u002F399833258\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1069,"date":1070,"description":1071,"extension":1072,"lang":1073,"meta":1074,"navigation":81,"path":1075,"readingMinutes":1076,"seo":1077,"standalone":1078,"stem":1079,"tags":1080,"tldr":1084,"updated":1070,"url":1085,"__hash__":1086},"content\u002Fen\u002FPython\u002Fpython-from-js-09-container-types-part-1.md","Learning Python From a JS Angle (9) — Container Types, Part 1","1002629111",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1062},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,30,33,119,128,131,141,144,185,188,215,222,228,235,238,274,277,283,286,351,354,413,416,420,423,553,556,569,572,626,633,659,665,691,694,701,748,755,799,805,808,814,817,820,827,834,876,882,885,931,936,946,993,1002,1008,1012,1015,1019,1052,1058],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"How did the BMI homework go? I don't know if you finished it or not, but time waits for no one here, so let's just move on to the next topic.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"what-are-container-types","What are container types?",[17,25,26],{},"The next thing I want to talk about is another kind of type in Python — container types.",[17,28,29],{},"In JavaScript this is basically what we call the object type. Python just calls it a container type instead.",[17,31,32],{},"So... what's a container type? You can think of a container type like a bunch of mugs or boxes you can stash all sorts of things in. Like I said, in JavaScript the container types are arrays and objects:",[34,35,40],"pre",{"className":36,"code":37,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","\u002F\u002F Array\nvar arr = ['Ray'];\n\n\u002F\u002F Object\nvar obj = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n","js","",[41,42,43,52,76,83,89,102,113],"code",{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,45,48],"span",{"class":46,"line":47},"line",1,[44,49,51],{"class":50},"sGBqm","\u002F\u002F Array\n",[44,53,55,59,63,66,69,73],{"class":46,"line":54},2,[44,56,58],{"class":57},"sOudu","var",[44,60,62],{"class":61},"s8XSl"," arr ",[44,64,65],{"class":57},"=",[44,67,68],{"class":61}," [",[44,70,72],{"class":71},"sWayO","'Ray'",[44,74,75],{"class":61},"];\n",[44,77,79],{"class":46,"line":78},3,[44,80,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},true,"\n",[44,84,86],{"class":46,"line":85},4,[44,87,88],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F Object\n",[44,90,92,94,97,99],{"class":46,"line":91},5,[44,93,58],{"class":57},[44,95,96],{"class":61}," obj ",[44,98,65],{"class":57},[44,100,101],{"class":61}," {\n",[44,103,105,108,110],{"class":46,"line":104},6,[44,106,107],{"class":61},"  name: ",[44,109,72],{"class":71},[44,111,112],{"class":61},",\n",[44,114,116],{"class":46,"line":115},7,[44,117,118],{"class":61},"};\n",[17,120,121,122,127],{},"(One thing to note here — arrays are still object types. For the why, check out ",[123,124,126],"a",{"href":125},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20201108\u002F33884\u002F","JavaScript Core Concepts (31) - Objects - Arrays"," (article in Mandarin).)",[17,129,130],{},"In Python they're not called arrays and objects — they're called lists and dictionaries:",[132,133,134,138],"ul",{},[135,136,137],"li",{},"Array === List",[135,139,140],{},"Object === Dictionaries",[17,142,143],{},"So is the syntax any different? For lists there's basically no big difference, but for dictionaries there's a small one:",[34,145,149],{"className":146,"code":147,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"language-py shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","# list\nlis = ['Ray']\n\n# dictionary\ndic = {\n  'name': 'Ray',\n}\n","py",[41,150,151,156,161,165,170,175,180],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,152,153],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,154,155],{},"# list\n",[44,157,158],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,159,160],{},"lis = ['Ray']\n",[44,162,163],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,164,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,166,167],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,168,169],{},"# dictionary\n",[44,171,172],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,173,174],{},"dic = {\n",[44,176,177],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,178,179],{},"  'name': 'Ray',\n",[44,181,182],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,183,184],{},"}\n",[17,186,187],{},"Why do I say dictionaries have a small difference? Let's flip back to JavaScript for a second. In a JavaScript object's properties, we can leave off the single\u002Fdouble quotes:",[34,189,191],{"className":36,"code":190,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var obj = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n",[41,192,193,203,211],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,194,195,197,199,201],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,196,58],{"class":57},[44,198,96],{"class":61},[44,200,65],{"class":57},[44,202,101],{"class":61},[44,204,205,207,209],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,206,107],{"class":61},[44,208,72],{"class":71},[44,210,112],{"class":61},[44,212,213],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,214,118],{"class":61},[17,216,217,218,221],{},"But in Python you can't leave off those quotes, otherwise you'll get a ",[41,219,220],{},"NameError: name 'name' is not defined",".",[17,223,224],{},[225,226],"img",{"alt":220,"src":227},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2017.27.23.png",[17,229,230,231,221],{},"Now, because of that error message, it means a property that isn't wrapped in single\u002Fdouble quotes is treated by Python as ",[232,233,234],"strong",{},"a variable",[17,236,237],{},"So we can boldly try something a little daring — what if I declare a variable and then use a dictionary property that isn't wrapped in quotes? What happens then?",[34,239,241],{"className":146,"code":240,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"name = 'myName'\n\ndic = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n}\n\nprint(dic) # ??\n",[41,242,243,248,252,256,261,265,269],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,244,245],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,246,247],{},"name = 'myName'\n",[44,249,250],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,251,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,253,254],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,255,174],{},[44,257,258],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,259,260],{},"  name: 'Ray',\n",[44,262,263],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,264,184],{},[44,266,267],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,268,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,270,271],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,272,273],{},"print(dic) # ??\n",[17,275,276],{},"And we can see it actually works fine:",[17,278,279],{},[225,280],{"alt":281,"src":282},"Ran successfully","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2017.30.02.png",[17,284,285],{},"Notice how this is a bit different from JavaScript? Normally JavaScript won't let you pass an object property in as a variable — no matter what, it gets turned into a string property. It just ignores it and lets you write it that way in terms of how it's displayed and written:",[34,287,289],{"className":36,"code":288,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var name = 'myName';\n\nvar obj = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n\nconsole.log(obj); \u002F\u002F { name: \"Ray\" }\n",[41,290,291,306,310,320,328,332,336],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,292,293,295,298,300,303],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,294,58],{"class":57},[44,296,297],{"class":61}," name ",[44,299,65],{"class":57},[44,301,302],{"class":71}," 'myName'",[44,304,305],{"class":61},";\n",[44,307,308],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,309,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,311,312,314,316,318],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,313,58],{"class":57},[44,315,96],{"class":61},[44,317,65],{"class":57},[44,319,101],{"class":61},[44,321,322,324,326],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,323,107],{"class":61},[44,325,72],{"class":71},[44,327,112],{"class":61},[44,329,330],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,331,118],{"class":61},[44,333,334],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,335,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,337,338,341,345,348],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,339,340],{"class":61},"console.",[44,342,344],{"class":343},"scAaK","log",[44,346,347],{"class":61},"(obj); ",[44,349,350],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F { name: \"Ray\" }\n",[17,352,353],{},"But if you really do hit that edge case where an object's property has to come from a variable, you can actually do it — you just have to use the bracket operator:",[34,355,357],{"className":36,"code":356,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var name = 'myName';\n\nvar obj = {\n  [name]: 'Ray',\n};\n\nconsole.log(obj); \u002F\u002F { myName: \"Ray\" }\n",[41,358,359,371,375,385,394,398,402],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,360,361,363,365,367,369],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,362,58],{"class":57},[44,364,297],{"class":61},[44,366,65],{"class":57},[44,368,302],{"class":71},[44,370,305],{"class":61},[44,372,373],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,374,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,376,377,379,381,383],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,378,58],{"class":57},[44,380,96],{"class":61},[44,382,65],{"class":57},[44,384,101],{"class":61},[44,386,387,390,392],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,388,389],{"class":61},"  [name]: ",[44,391,72],{"class":71},[44,393,112],{"class":61},[44,395,396],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,397,118],{"class":61},[44,399,400],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,401,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,403,404,406,408,410],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,405,340],{"class":61},[44,407,344],{"class":343},[44,409,347],{"class":61},[44,411,412],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F { myName: \"Ray\" }\n",[17,414,415],{},"See! The effect is basically the same, it's just a different way of writing it.",[12,417,419],{"id":418},"getting-values-out-of-container-types","Getting values out of container types",[17,421,422],{},"Next up is pulling values out of containers. Is grabbing values from lists and dictionaries different from JavaScript? Let's first look back at how we get values from objects and arrays in JavaScript:",[34,424,426],{"className":36,"code":425,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"\u002F\u002F array access\nvar arr = ['Ray'];\narr[0]; \u002F\u002F Ray\n\nvar obj = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n};\n\u002F\u002F dot operator\nobj.name; \u002F\u002F Ray\n\u002F\u002F bracket operator\nobj['name'];\n\n\u002F\u002F bracket operator + variable\nvar variable = 'name';\nobj[variable]; \u002F\u002F Ray\n",[41,427,428,433,447,462,466,476,484,488,494,502,508,519,524,530,545],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,429,430],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,431,432],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F array access\n",[44,434,435,437,439,441,443,445],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,436,58],{"class":57},[44,438,62],{"class":61},[44,440,65],{"class":57},[44,442,68],{"class":61},[44,444,72],{"class":71},[44,446,75],{"class":61},[44,448,449,452,456,459],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,450,451],{"class":61},"arr[",[44,453,455],{"class":454},"stw71","0",[44,457,458],{"class":61},"]; ",[44,460,461],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F Ray\n",[44,463,464],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,465,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,467,468,470,472,474],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,469,58],{"class":57},[44,471,96],{"class":61},[44,473,65],{"class":57},[44,475,101],{"class":61},[44,477,478,480,482],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,479,107],{"class":61},[44,481,72],{"class":71},[44,483,112],{"class":61},[44,485,486],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,487,118],{"class":61},[44,489,491],{"class":46,"line":490},8,[44,492,493],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F dot operator\n",[44,495,497,500],{"class":46,"line":496},9,[44,498,499],{"class":61},"obj.name; ",[44,501,461],{"class":50},[44,503,505],{"class":46,"line":504},10,[44,506,507],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F bracket operator\n",[44,509,511,514,517],{"class":46,"line":510},11,[44,512,513],{"class":61},"obj[",[44,515,516],{"class":71},"'name'",[44,518,75],{"class":61},[44,520,522],{"class":46,"line":521},12,[44,523,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,525,527],{"class":46,"line":526},13,[44,528,529],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F bracket operator + variable\n",[44,531,533,535,538,540,543],{"class":46,"line":532},14,[44,534,58],{"class":57},[44,536,537],{"class":61}," variable ",[44,539,65],{"class":57},[44,541,542],{"class":71}," 'name'",[44,544,305],{"class":61},[44,546,548,551],{"class":46,"line":547},15,[44,549,550],{"class":61},"obj[variable]; ",[44,552,461],{"class":50},[17,554,555],{},"Basically in JavaScript there are two main ways to get values:",[132,557,558,563],{},[135,559,560,561],{},"Dot operator - ",[41,562,221],{},[135,564,565,566],{},"Bracket operator - ",[41,567,568],{},"[]",[17,570,571],{},"So is it the same in Python? If it is, how do we write it? Let's look at an example:",[34,573,575],{"className":146,"code":574,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"# list access\nlis = ['Ray']\nlis[0] # 'Ray'\n\ndic = {\n  'name': 'Ray',\n}\n\ndis['name'] # 'Ray'\nvariable = 'name'\ndic[variable] # 'Ray'\n",[41,576,577,582,586,591,595,599,603,607,611,616,621],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,578,579],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,580,581],{},"# list access\n",[44,583,584],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,585,160],{},[44,587,588],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,589,590],{},"lis[0] # 'Ray'\n",[44,592,593],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,594,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,596,597],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,598,174],{},[44,600,601],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,602,179],{},[44,604,605],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,606,184],{},[44,608,609],{"class":46,"line":490},[44,610,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,612,613],{"class":46,"line":496},[44,614,615],{},"dis['name'] # 'Ray'\n",[44,617,618],{"class":46,"line":504},[44,619,620],{},"variable = 'name'\n",[44,622,623],{"class":46,"line":510},[44,624,625],{},"dic[variable] # 'Ray'\n",[17,627,628,629,632],{},"You'll notice in the example above I didn't use the dot operator to get values. That's because Python can't grab values with the dot operator the way JavaScript can. But Python does have some pretty special and fun methods for it, like ",[41,630,631],{},"get()",":",[34,634,636],{"className":146,"code":635,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"dic = {\n  'name': 'Ray',\n}\n\ndic.get('name', 'N\u002FA') # 'Ray'\n",[41,637,638,642,646,650,654],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,639,640],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,641,174],{},[44,643,644],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,645,179],{},[44,647,648],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,649,184],{},[44,651,652],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,653,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,655,656],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,657,658],{},"dic.get('name', 'N\u002FA') # 'Ray'\n",[17,660,661,662,664],{},"So what's ",[41,663,631],{}," for? It mainly takes two arguments. The first is the property name you want to grab, and the second is what to hand back to you if that property name doesn't exist. For example:",[34,666,668],{"className":146,"code":667,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"dic = {\n  'name': 'Ray',\n}\n\ndic.get('qq', 'no key') # 'no key'\n",[41,669,670,674,678,682,686],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,671,672],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,673,174],{},[44,675,676],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,677,179],{},[44,679,680],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,681,184],{},[44,683,684],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,685,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,687,688],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,689,690],{},"dic.get('qq', 'no key') # 'no key'\n",[17,692,693],{},"We can see this way of getting values avoids the error when a dictionary property doesn't exist, and you can even customize the error message. Pretty great, right?",[17,695,696,697,700],{},"Wait — we never actually talked about what happens when a dictionary property doesn't exist, right? In JavaScript, when we grab a non-existent object property we get ",[41,698,699],{},"undefined",", and the code keeps running:",[34,702,704],{"className":36,"code":703,"language":38,"meta":39,"style":39},"var obj = {};\n\nconsole.log(obj.myName); \u002F\u002F undefined\nconsole.log('I still run');\n",[41,705,706,717,721,733],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,707,708,710,712,714],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,709,58],{"class":57},[44,711,96],{"class":61},[44,713,65],{"class":57},[44,715,716],{"class":61}," {};\n",[44,718,719],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,720,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,722,723,725,727,730],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,724,340],{"class":61},[44,726,344],{"class":343},[44,728,729],{"class":61},"(obj.myName); ",[44,731,732],{"class":50},"\u002F\u002F undefined\n",[44,734,735,737,739,742,745],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,736,340],{"class":61},[44,738,344],{"class":343},[44,740,741],{"class":61},"(",[44,743,744],{"class":71},"'I still run'",[44,746,747],{"class":61},");\n",[17,749,750,751,754],{},"But in Python it just stops the code dead with a ",[41,752,753],{},"'KeyError: xxx'"," error message:",[34,756,758],{"className":146,"code":757,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"name = 'myName'\n\ndic = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n}\n\nprint(dic[name])\nprint(dic['qq'])\nprint('I cannot run anymore')\n",[41,759,760,764,768,772,776,780,784,789,794],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,761,762],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,763,247],{},[44,765,766],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,767,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,769,770],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,771,174],{},[44,773,774],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,775,260],{},[44,777,778],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,779,184],{},[44,781,782],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,783,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,785,786],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,787,788],{},"print(dic[name])\n",[44,790,791],{"class":46,"line":490},[44,792,793],{},"print(dic['qq'])\n",[44,795,796],{"class":46,"line":496},[44,797,798],{},"print('I cannot run anymore')\n",[17,800,801],{},[225,802],{"alt":803,"src":804},"KeyError","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2020.46.12.png",[17,806,807],{},"Okay, at this point you might be stressing out — do I really have to write out the property name correctly every single time?",[17,809,810],{},[225,811],{"alt":812,"src":813},"Stressed out","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2021.06.32.png",[17,815,816],{},"Isn't there a way to say \"when this value doesn't exist, just write in a default property and value\"?",[17,818,819],{},"The answer is yes!",[17,821,822,823,826],{},"This is where you use the ",[41,824,825],{},"setdefault()"," method. It also takes two arguments — the first is the property name you want to set\u002Fget, and the second is the value to write in by default if that property doesn't exist.",[17,828,829,830,833],{},"For example, say when a property doesn't exist, we want \"",[41,831,832],{},"This is a sentence","\" to show up:",[34,835,837],{"className":146,"code":836,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"name = 'myName'\n\ndic = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n}\n\nprint(dic[name])\nprint(dic.setdefault('qq', 'This is a sentence'))\nprint('I cannot run anymore')\n",[41,838,839,843,847,851,855,859,863,867,872],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,840,841],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,842,247],{},[44,844,845],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,846,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,848,849],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,850,174],{},[44,852,853],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,854,260],{},[44,856,857],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,858,184],{},[44,860,861],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,862,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,864,865],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,866,788],{},[44,868,869],{"class":46,"line":490},[44,870,871],{},"print(dic.setdefault('qq', 'This is a sentence'))\n",[44,873,874],{"class":46,"line":496},[44,875,798],{},[17,877,878],{},[225,879],{"alt":880,"src":881},"setdefault","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2020.50.59.png",[17,883,884],{},"On the flip side, if that property already exists in the dictionary, it'll keep its original value and won't get overwritten:",[34,886,888],{"className":146,"code":887,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"name = 'myName'\n\ndic = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n  'qq': 'I already exist'\n}\n\nprint(dic[name])\nprint(dic.setdefault('qq', 'This is a sentence'))\nprint('I cannot run anymore')\n",[41,889,890,894,898,902,906,911,915,919,923,927],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,891,892],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,893,247],{},[44,895,896],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,897,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,899,900],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,901,174],{},[44,903,904],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,905,260],{},[44,907,908],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,909,910],{},"  'qq': 'I already exist'\n",[44,912,913],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,914,184],{},[44,916,917],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,918,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,920,921],{"class":46,"line":490},[44,922,788],{},[44,924,925],{"class":46,"line":496},[44,926,871],{},[44,928,929],{"class":46,"line":504},[44,930,798],{},[17,932,933],{},[225,934],{"alt":880,"src":935},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-06-26%2020.52.34.png",[17,937,938,939,941,942,945],{},"Once you've got ",[41,940,880],{}," down, you can also use it to add a dictionary under ",[41,943,944],{},"qq"," — basically the nested-object idea:",[34,947,949],{"className":146,"code":948,"language":148,"meta":39,"style":39},"name = 'myName'\n\ndic = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n}\n\nprint(dic[name])\nprint(dic.setdefault('qq', {}))\nprint(dic['qq'].setdefault('sayHi', 'Hello Ray')) # could also be written as dic.setdefault('qq', {}).setdefault('sayHi', 'Hello Ray')\nprint('I cannot run anymore')\n",[41,950,951,955,959,963,967,971,975,979,984,989],{"__ignoreMap":39},[44,952,953],{"class":46,"line":47},[44,954,247],{},[44,956,957],{"class":46,"line":54},[44,958,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,960,961],{"class":46,"line":78},[44,962,174],{},[44,964,965],{"class":46,"line":85},[44,966,260],{},[44,968,969],{"class":46,"line":91},[44,970,184],{},[44,972,973],{"class":46,"line":104},[44,974,82],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":81},[44,976,977],{"class":46,"line":115},[44,978,788],{},[44,980,981],{"class":46,"line":490},[44,982,983],{},"print(dic.setdefault('qq', {}))\n",[44,985,986],{"class":46,"line":496},[44,987,988],{},"print(dic['qq'].setdefault('sayHi', 'Hello Ray')) # could also be written as dic.setdefault('qq', {}).setdefault('sayHi', 'Hello Ray')\n",[44,990,991],{"class":46,"line":504},[44,992,798],{},[17,994,995,996,998,999,1001],{},"I'm sure you've now got a real feel for how lovely ",[41,997,631],{}," and ",[41,1000,825],{}," both are. Which one to actually use, I'll leave that for you to think about.",[17,1003,1004],{},[225,1005],{"alt":1006,"src":1007},"How should I choose","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FPython\u002F%E5%BE%9E%20JavaScript%20%E8%A7%92%E5%BA%A6%E5%AD%B8%20Python\u002F1629121235164.png",[12,1009,1011],{"id":1010},"a-word-from-the-author","A word from the author",[17,1013,1014],{},"A friend asked me how I make my Hua Diao drunken chicken rolls, so I figured I'd share the ingredients while I'm at it. Basically it's 200cc of Hua Diao wine, 100cc of rice wine (I use Tianwei rice wine, but you could go with the red-label rice wine), and white pepper to taste — that simple. If you want to throw in some angelica root and all that, you can too.",[12,1016,1018],{"id":1017},"about-the-rabbits","About the Rabbits",[132,1020,1021,1029,1037,1045],{},[135,1022,1023],{},[123,1024,1028],{"href":1025,"rel":1026},"https:\u002F\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[1027],"nofollow","Tailwind CSS Taiwan Official Site",[135,1030,1031,1036],{},[123,1032,1035],{"href":1033,"rel":1034},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Ftailwindcss.tw",[1027],"Tailwind CSS Taiwan"," (Facebook page)",[135,1038,1039,1044],{},[123,1040,1043],{"href":1041,"rel":1042},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Fgroups\u002Ftailwindcss.taiwan",[1027],"Rabbit Sect × Tailwind CSS Taiwan"," (Facebook group)",[135,1046,1047],{},[123,1048,1051],{"href":1049,"rel":1050},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002Flalarabbits-%E5%85%94%E5%85%94%E6%95%99%E5%A4%A7%E6%9C%AC%E7%87%9F-102150975410839\u002F",[1027],"Rabbit Sect HQ",[17,1053,1054],{},[225,1055],{"alt":1056,"src":1057},"Rabbit magic knows no bounds","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FPwE2UE9.jpg",[1059,1060,1061],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sGBqm, html code.shiki .sGBqm{--shiki-light:#6A737D;--shiki-default:#6A737D;--shiki-dark:#BDC4CC}html pre.shiki code .sOudu, html code.shiki .sOudu{--shiki-light:#D73A49;--shiki-default:#D73A49;--shiki-dark:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .s8XSl, html code.shiki .s8XSl{--shiki-light:#24292E;--shiki-default:#24292E;--shiki-dark:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sWayO, html code.shiki .sWayO{--shiki-light:#032F62;--shiki-default:#032F62;--shiki-dark:#ADDCFF}html .light .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-light);background: var(--shiki-light-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-light-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-light-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-light-text-decoration);}html.light .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-light);background: var(--shiki-light-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-light-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-light-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-light-text-decoration);}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: v